s together with fine-grained ethnographic observations and urban history to examine the ways that immigration, housing, ethnic change, gentrification, race, class, and gender have affected the neighborhood over time. Providing unique access to the nuances of inner-city life, The Tenants of East Harlem shows how roots sink so quickly in a community that has always hosted the transient, how new immigrants are challenging the claims of the old, and how that cycle is threatened as never before by the specter of gentrification.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunity development, UrbanzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEthnicityzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aGentrificationzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSociology, UrbanzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban anthropologyzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrican americans.  aamerica.  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  achinese americans.  aclass differences.  aeast harlem.  aethnic differences.  agender studies.  agentrification.  aharlem residents.  ahousing.  aimmigrant experiences.  ainner city life.  aitalian americans.  anew york.  anonfiction biography.  aoral histories.  apersonal stories.  apuerto ricans.  arace issues.  asociology.  astreet life.  atransient living.  aundocumented mexicans.  aunited states.  aurban history.  aurban life.  awest africa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024427640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093954740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939547/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-201